etymologies: Middle English; earliest use found in Otuel. From stick + -ed

definitions: Of a pig: that has had a knife thrust into its neck; stuck. Chiefly in similative phrases. Compare "stuck". Now rare (chiefly British regional in later use).

etymologies: early 18th century; earliest use found in Samuel Sewall (1652–1730), judge and diarist in America. From stick + -ed

definitions: Of timber: stacked with sticks inserted between the layers to facilitate the circulation of air during seasoning.
Of a plant: supported by a stick.

etymologies: late 18th century; earliest use found in Tench Coxe (1755–1824). From stick + -ed

definitions: Provided or constructed with a stick or sticks, especially of a specified type or number.
